<s docid="FT922-14265" num="6" wdcount="11"> SAM WALTON was arguably the most 
important retailer of his generation.</s>

<s docid="AP890323-0234" num="36" wdcount="25"> The seeds of the Wal-Mart empire were 
sown when Sam and his brother James L., or Bud, opened the first Wal-Mart 
Discount City in 1962.</s>

<s docid="AP890323-0234" num="14" wdcount="17"> Paying unexpected calls on stores is 
one way Walton has kept in close touch with everyday goings-on.</s>

<s docid="FT922-14265" num="8" wdcount="28"> By 1991 the chain's sales had risen to 
nearly Dollars 44bn, making it the world's largest retailer in terms of 
revenues, and the Walton family probably America's richest.</s>

<s docid="FT922-14265" num="10" wdcount="16"> The chain's success stemmed both from Mr 
Walton's personality and willingness to challenge accepted retailing 
orthodoxy.</s>

<s docid="AP890711-0223" num="33" wdcount="29"> When Walton first made the Forbes list 
of richest Americans, recalled Little Rock investment banker Warren Simpson, 
calls came in from all over about the billionaire from the Ozarks.</s>

<s docid="AP890323-0234" num="27" wdcount="13"> One of the most sensitive subjects for 
Walton is the fortune he's amassed.</s>

<s docid="FT944-12170" num="18" wdcount="15"> One strength the authors identify is 
Wal-Mart's ability to copy and adapt from other retailers.</s>

<s docid="FT944-12170" num="21" wdcount="40"> Walton learned from them all, but was 
unique in taking his discount stores into small towns of a few thousand people, 
where shoppers used to travelling long distances were delighted to have a cut-
price store nearby selling everything they needed.</s>
